Currently when you add a new service, the field inputs are validated using object configuration types. The validation performed is usually a simple type checking and there is no mechanism in place to extend the validation. Eg. cant block negative number inputs for a number field.

Please refactor class ComponentsVersionsProjectTabPanel.

Currently it has method (written in pseudo-code)

{code}
String getHtml(Browser) {
    parameters = new map;
    fill parameters;
    return descripitor.getHtml("view", parameters); // render
}
{code}

It makes hard to extend this class. We need to add several additional parameters to that map, to render page with these additional objects. Currently we have to copy this class and hack it. This makes hard transition of existing code to new JIRA version. We suggest refactoring:

{code}
String getHtml(browser) {
    parameters = getParameters(browser);
    return descripitor.getHtml("view", parameters);
}

Map getParameters(browser) {
    parameters = new map;
    fill parameters;
    return parameters;
}
{code}

So we could override method getParamters, call super.getParameters() to set default JIRA attributes, and add several ours:

{code}
class YandexComponentsVersionsProjectTabPanel extends ComponentsVersionsProjectTabPanel {
    Map getParameters(browser) {
        parameters = super.getParameters(browser);
        add our specific parameters;
        return parameters;
    }
}
{code}

This make our changes compatible with newer JIRA versions.

If you write codes to bypass the permission query, you will only get it working if you're using standard queries, i.e. parameters are not {{IssueCommentParameter}}, {{IssueParameter}}, {{CommentParameter}}, e.g. CustomFieldParams.

This happens because the trick used in {{LuceneQueryCreator}} is just not smart enough:

{code:java}
            // we need at least one parameter, so if there aren't any others - add the permissions parameter
            if (standardQueries.isEmpty())
            {
                booleanStandardQuery.add(permissionQuery, BooleanClause.Occur.MUST);
            }
{code}

For example, using a {{new SearchRequest(true)}}, [searching on Customfield|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/How+to+search+for+Issues+based+on+CustomField] returns a list of issues, but  using {{ProjectParameter(new Long(10001))}} doesn't unless you specify a remote user, e.g.

{code:java}
List searched = sProvider.search(sRequest, remoteUser, PagerFilter.getUnlimitedFilter()).getIssues();
{code}

